Her name is Gertie Heckleman and this is a classic mom story…

A few many years ago… after a very long wait, I finally got to plop onto the table w/ @robbanksofamerica to snag a pinup gal tattoo. 

My only requirements? She be a beautiful gal and holding 🍕. 

When I saw the drawing I immediately said “my mom will kill me, nice Jewish girls don’t get tattoos like this.”

Then I took two shots of whiskey and rolled my sleeve up. I wasn’t about to let someone else get this one-of-a-kind 🍕 pinup gal #tattoo

The next day I told my mom and she was devastated I got another tattoo (I have quite a few). 

So devastated she didn’t talk to me until the next day (which was an eternity for us both).

“I want to name her.” Sure ok mom, if that’s all it takes for your approval. “Gertie Heckelman a nice Jewish girl from Italy!” At least she was wearing shoes 💁🏻‍♀️

Ok mom, so be it.

Where did the name come from? My mom recalled finding it on a rolled up piece of paper in a sock drawer when she was little. It’s a bit of a mystery as to who this was and will most likely forever be.

While my mom had always been so against tattoos, BUT she was always so proud of having named Gertie and carried a photo of her to share w/ everyone she knows. 

I guess I do in deed have good taste in women (and tattoos) after all. Thanks for always making me smile Ms Gertie Heckelman.

OG NY style before the bake. If you’ve ever been inside of a pre-1940’s era coal-fired pizzeria, you’d recognize this Jackson Pollack style sauce application at first 👀.

The original NY style pizza makers placed cheese on bottom, sauce on top to help protect the cheese from burning in coal-fired ovens.

Unlike NY style slice pizza, the older coal-fired ovens bake at hotter temps (650-750). The higher the temps, the more the cheese can burn.

Personally… I’ve always referred to the sauce as the Bodyguard.

You need so LITTLE sauce for this style due to the oil found in aged mozzareblock cheese with added oil to preserve the shelf life).

Coal-fired 🍕 traditionally uses sliced, cubed hand-torn aged mozzarella.

Personally, I do a blend of both eras and switch between whole sliced and shredded. Depends what I’ve got open and on hand. 

Is this oil a bad thing? Nope! It creates that magical 🍕 juice great for dipping crust in.

And it’s a dealbreaker for me on a date if she blots her slice… so 💁🏻‍♀️

Check out @julianaspizza Sam’s on Court, and @johnsofbleeckerstreet for some OG NY-style 🍕 

Check out @brooklyndop @wheatedbrooklyn and @coniglios (in Jersey baby) for some post 1940s NY style 🍕 paying homage to the OG.

I don’t think a lot of people realize the amount of work that goes into a POPUP. 

Right now, it’s just me and on busier nights, I bring on an assistant to help take orders, expedite the 🍕, and field hellos from friends near and far.

A POPUP is typically booked out 1-3 months in advance—on occasion a week before if I can fit it in or if a venue has a slot I really want.

Going into an event week, I have to launch and pre-sell pizzas. I do this for 2 reasons: to give my regulars a chance to snag a pie w/o the wait and to help draw a crowd on what would normally be a slow night for the venue.

Yes, I said slow night. We are booked to help generate more business on a slower weekday night most times.

The week of the event is prep time til event day. Making dough, prepping ingredients and on event day, loading up all equipment into an Uber.

1-1.5hrs of setup before you arrive then a cool 3 hours of bake time, then another 1.5hrs to breakdown before taking Uber back to my kitchen to unload and clean.

Most events, customers might wait anywhere from 20 minutes to 2 hours for a 🍕! My events generally start w/ a line of fans eager to get a pie. And only once in 3yrs have I had a customer complain about the wait.

Honestly, I’m not sure which I love baking and eating more… the 🍕 or the 🥖 at @spaccanapolichicago both of which come from the same exact batch of Neapolitan dough.

Ask me the most important thing I learned last week? 

“1, 2, 3, dome.”

Honestly, it’s seems so simple but it isn’t. But it is. But not entirely.

Nobody had yet shared this critical baking rule in a wood fired oven w/ me until Jonathan stood 15’ from me making focaccia as he watched me bake. 

Don’t get me wrong, I’ve been given and picked up many tips along the way, but this one in particular just clicked and made my baking that much better. 

3 quarter turns then dome on the final 4th turn. Each turn outside of the oven and the pie has to be placed exactly where it landed prior to turn 1 or you’ll scold the bottom.

I wish I knew this 4 years ago so hear I am sharing one big thing I learned last week to help y’all bake better 🍕 whether it’s in a masterpiece of an oven like this, or an @oonihq w/ the fire in the wrapping around the side or back.
